<hl>
<seg id=1> Thai Finance Minister Tarrin left for Japan, talking about loans. </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> French News Agency, Bangkok Thai Finance Minister Tarrin left for Tokyo yesterday, discussing a part of the US$30 billion (48.6 billion Singapore dollars) loans to Thailand that Japan invested to save the financial crisis of Asian economic system. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> He said that during the 4-day visit in Japan, he would discuss it further, but he could not guess how much Japan would give to Thailand. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Tarrin told a reporter at the Bangkok International Airport: "I reported the outline of the loan to Prime Minister Chuan Leepkai yesterday, but we haven't decide the figures yet since Japan hasn't notified us. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> He said that he wished to get a low rate and generous repayment conditions from the plan. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> He said that he would talk separately with the officials of the Japanese Ministry of Trade and the Ministry of Industry to discuss the new support to Thai industry and the agricultural reform. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Japanese Minister of Finance Kiichi Migazawa announced a set of US$30 billion loans at the 7-country group meeting on 3 October. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> In a short period, Japan will allocateUS$15 billion to support the areas of trade, finance and investment, etc. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Japan will provide direct financial support through loans from the Japanese Import and Export Bank and purchase some of the Asian public debt, and Japan will provide the Asian countries with loan of Japanese Yen. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> It also will guarantee the loans to the banks of the Asian countries and issue Asian bonds, and it will help them raise money from the world. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> Kiichi Migazawa's set of aid plans are no small matter to Thailand, since Thailand has postponed a plan of issuing US$500millioin world bonds last month. </seg>
<seg id=12> Thailand wants to use the money to bring its economy more circulating capital. </seg>
<seg id=13> The Thai economy has been severely stricken by high loan capital and the new global market storm. </seg>
</p>
